    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">LYMPHOMA: EPIDEMIOLOGY AND THE ROLE OF IMMUNOHISTOCHEMISTRY AS A DIAGNOSTIC TECHNIQUE</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">ABHISHEK KUMAR R</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">LYMPHOMA, EPIDEMIOLOGY, IMMUNOHISTOCHEMISTRY, DIAGNOSTIC TECHNIQUE</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">1-May-2008 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM UNIVERSITY</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">4080</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">The world has witnessed a substantial increase in the number of cancer cases
reported in the past decade. This can be attributed to several reasons, most of them
stemming up from the ever changing social scene which has given rise to changing
food habits, increase in alcohol and tobacco consumption and drug addiction. Contact
with environmental elements such as harmful gases and toxic pest repellants also play
a part. If the current trend persists, the prediction made by WHO in its most recent
World Cancer Report, of a fifty percent increase in cancer incidence from ten million
to fifteen million cases by 2020, may hold some credibility.
Lymphoma is fast becoming an area of concern as it is one of the leading
causes of cancer deaths. The diagnosis of lymphoma relies primarily on invasive
tissue biopsy, as noninvasive diagnostic tests are generally insufficient to define a
disease process of cancer. The conventional histopathology based on light
microscopy, however, has recently been complemented with ultrastructure,
immunohistochemistry and molecular diagnostics. Molecular medicine has led to the
discovery and application of molecular tumor markers, which make histology more
accurate and additionally help to prognosticate cancer.
Among all the lymphoma cases reported at Stanley Medical College in the
year, the majority were cancers of the gastrointestinal tract, especially of the stomach,
small intestine, duodenum and ileum. The other sites of lymphoma were the lymph
nodes, brain and liver.
The lymphomas mostly are diagnosed by biopsies or core biopsies and
histological interpretation. Immunohistochemistry (IHC) is used as a confirmatory
step in difficult cases.
This dissertation aims at throwing light on the importance and effectiveness of
IHC as a diagnostic tool for difficult lymphoma cases where performing biopsies
alone donâ€™t suffice. We deal mainly with the role of immunohistochemical staining
with CD3, CD20, CD45 and Cytokeratin markers in diagnosis and differentiation of
various lymphomas.
9
We have also dealt with the statistical data available through the existing
literature and medical records of the Stanley Medical College to comprehend the
pattern of incidence of the various lymphomas in India and all over the world.</td></tr>
